Step-by-Step Walkthrough

Parent Class (Vehicle)
We define a class called Vehicle. This class will represent any general vehicle, and it will store basic information like the make (brand) and the model.

class Vehicle:
    def __init__(self, make, model):
        self.make = make
        self.model = model
The __init__ method is the constructor. Whenever we create a Vehicle object, we pass in a make (like "Toyota") and a model (like "Corolla"), and these get stored in the object.

We also define a method called display_info(), which will print out the vehicle’s make and model.

    def display_info(self):
        print(f"Vehicle Make: {self.make}")
        print(f"Vehicle Model: {self.model}")
Here, self refers to the object we create. When we call display_info(), it will print out the make and model of that specific vehicle.

Child Class (Car)
Now we create a Car class that inherits from Vehicle. This means a car is a type of vehicle, so it should get the make and model from the parent class. But we also add something extra—like the number of doors, which is specific to a car.

class Car(Vehicle):
    def __init__(self, make, model, num_doors):
        # Call the parent class (Vehicle) constructor
        super().__init__(make, model)  # This passes make and model to Vehicle
        self.num_doors = num_doors  # Add the new attribute for cars
In this constructor, we still need make and model, just like in Vehicle, so we call the parent class’s __init__() using super(). Then we add a new attribute—num_doors—specific to cars.

After that, we override the display_info() method to add more details, so it first calls the parent method (to print make and model), and then prints the number of doors.

    def display_info(self):
        super().display_info()  # Call parent method first
        print(f"Number of Doors: {self.num_doors}")

Create Objects
Now we create an object of Vehicle and an object of Car.

vehicle = Vehicle("Toyota", "Corolla")
vehicle.display_info()

When we call vehicle.display_info(), it prints:

Vehicle Make: Toyota
Vehicle Model: Corolla

Then we create a car object:

car = Car("BMW", "X5", 4)
car.display_info()

Now the car will print:

Vehicle Make: BMW
Vehicle Model: X5
Number of Doors: 4
Summary of What’s Happening:
The parent class Vehicle defines a basic template for any vehicle.
The child class Car inherits all the properties of Vehicle (make and model) but also adds something new (number of doors).
We use super() in the child class to call the parent’s constructor, so we don’t have to rewrite the code.

In short, inheritance lets us build specialized versions of a general concept—like a car being a specialized type of vehicle!

